               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300415-224-person1969">
                  THOMAS 
                  RUSSELL
               <interp inst="t18300415-224-person1969" type="surname" value="RUSSELL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-224-person1969" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-224-person1969" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a <rs id="t18300415-224-viclabel1243" type="occupation">seafaring-man</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300415-224-victim1968 t18300415-224-viclabel1243"></join>. I fell in with the prisoner on the 6th of April as I was going on board, below <placeName id="t18300415-224-crimeloc1244">Shadwell church</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18300415-224-crimeloc1244" type="placeName" value="Shadwell church"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18300415-224-crimeloc1244" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300415-224-off1241 t18300415-224-crimeloc1244"></join> - there was another woman with her; they asked me to treat them with some gin, which I did - I sat down myself, and smoked a pipe; I then asked if one of them could accommodate me with a bed - the prisoner took me home, and put me to bed at No. 4, close by Shadwell church; I went to a room up two pair of stairs, and went to bed - I put my trousers under my pillow; I am quite sure my watch was then safe in my fob - I felt it, rolled it up, and put my trousers under my pillow; I laid looking at the prisoner, who kept walking about the room - I had given her 3s. for the bed; she came to the bed, took my trousers, and went to the table; she came back, and put the trousers under my head again - she then went out at the door; I waited five or ten minutes - she did not return; I got up, took my trousers, and overhauled them - I missed my watch and seals; being in a strange place I did not know what to do, so I laid down, and went to sleep till the morning -I fastened the door, and had nothing to lose but my trousers - in the morning I went to a friend's, and we got a Police-officer; we at last went to the King's Head, and there she was laying in the tap-room beastly drunk - she was not<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183004150103"></xptr>drunk when she was in the room with me; I had had five or six glasses of grog, but was quite sensible - the landlady produced my watch out of the bar.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300415-224-person1970">
                  MARY 
                  COZENS
               <interp inst="t18300415-224-person1970" type="surname" value="COZENS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-224-person1970" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-224-person1970" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the wife of John Cozens; he keeps the King's Head, Brook-street. The prosecutor came there on the 5th of April with the prisoner - he asked her what she would take; she said a glass of gin - he took a glass of porter, and they talked together; the prisoner came to my house next morning; two officers went by, and said to me, "Are you aware you have a pane of glass broken?" I said to the prisoner, "You must pay for that glass;" she said she had no money, but she would leave security, and she gave me the same watch which I gave to the officer.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300415-224-person1971">
                  BENJAMIN 
                  HAYWOOD
               <interp inst="t18300415-224-person1971" type="surname" value="HAYWOOD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-224-person1971" type="given" value="BENJAMIN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-224-person1971" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Police-officer. I was at the public-house when the watch was given to Mr. Cozens - the prisoner was there beastly drunk.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300415-224-person1972">
                  RICHARD 
                  HEMMINGS
               <interp inst="t18300415-224-person1972" type="surname" value="HEMMINGS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-224-person1972" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-224-person1972" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I went there, and saw the prisoner drunk.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I met the prosecutor; he asked where I was going - I said home; we went to the public-house, and had a quartern of gin; we then went home, and had some more - we then went to two other houses, and had more; we got very tipsy indeed - we went home; he said he had no money, but he would give me his watch to keep till he gave me 5s. - I said, "I don't like to take it; you won't say that I took it from you?" he said, "No; I know what I do when I am drunk, as well as when I am sober;" I left it at Mrs. Cozens' - I sat down there a minute or two, and there were two or three young chaps there - my head went against the glass, and broke it; I said, "I have nothing to pay, but this watch that a man left in my hands."</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18300415-224-verdict1245" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18300415-224-verdict1245" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 22. - <rs id="t18300415-224-punish1246" type="punishmentDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18300415-224-punish1246" type="punishmentCategory" value="transport"></interp>
                     <join result="defendantPunishment" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300415-224-defend1966 t18300415-224-punish1246"></join>
               Transported for Life
            </rs>.</p>
